SIMPLE: mouth
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mouth
<hw>Mouth</hw> <pr>(mouth)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Mouths</plw> <pr>(mou⟦th⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>mouth</ets>,
<ets>mu⟦thorn⟧</ets>, AS. <ets>m⟦umac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>mond</ets>, OS. <ets>m⟦umac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>, G. <ets>mund</ets>, Icel.
<ets>mu⟦edh⟧r</ets>, <ets>munnr</ets>, Sw. <ets>mun</ets>, Dan.
<ets>mund</ets>, Goth. <ets>mun⟦thorn⟧s</ets>, and possibly L.
<ets>mentum</ets> chin; or cf. D. <ets>muil</ets> mouth, muzzle, G.
<ets>maul</ets>, OHG. <ets>m⟦umac⟧la</ets>, Icel. <ets>m⟦umac⟧li</ets>,
and Skr. <ets>mukha</ets> mouth.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The opening
through which an animal receives food; the aperture between the jaws or
between the lips; also, the cavity, containing the
<contains>tongue</contains> and <contains>teeth</contains>, between the
lips and the pharynx; the buccal cavity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>An opening affording
entrance or exit; orifice; aperture;</def> as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The
opening of a vessel by which it is filled or emptied, charged or
discharged; <as>as, the <ex>mouth</ex> of a jar or pitcher; the
<ex>mouth</ex> of the lacteal vessels, etc.</as></def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>The opening or entrance of any cavity, as a cave, pit, well, or
den.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The opening of a piece of ordnance, through
which it is discharged.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>The opening through
which the waters of a river or any stream are discharged.</def>
<sd>(e)</sd> <def>The entrance into a harbor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Saddlery)</fld> <def>The crosspiece of a bridle
bit, which enters the mouth of an animal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A principal speaker; one who utters the common
opinion; a mouthpiece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every coffeehouse has some particular statesman belonging to it,
who is the <qex>mouth</qex> of the street where he lives.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Cry; voice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Speech; language; testimony.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That in the <qex>mouth</qex> of two or three witnesses every word
may be established.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xviii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A wry face; a grimace; a mow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Counterfeit sad looks,⟦br⟧
Make <qex>mouths</qex> upon me when I turn my back.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Down at the mouth</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Down in the mouth</b></col></mcol>, <cd>chapfallen; of dejected
countenance; depressed; discouraged.</cd> <mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark>
-- <col><b>Mouth friend</b></col>, <cd>one who professes friendship
insincerely.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Mouth glass</b></col>, <cd>a
small mirror for inspecting the mouth or teeth.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouth
honor</b></col>, <cd>honor given in words, but not felt.</cd>
<au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Mouth organ</b></col>. <fld>(Mus.)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Pan's pipes</cd>. See <er>Pandean</er>. <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>An harmonicon.</cd> -- <col><b>Mouth pipe</b></col>, <cd>an organ
pipe with a lip or plate to cut the escaping air and make a sound.</cd>
-- <col><b>To stop the mouth</b></col>, <cd>to silence or be silent; to
put to shame; to confound.</cd> -- <col><b>To put one's foot in one's
mouth</b></col>, <cd>to say something which causes one
embarrassment.</cd> -- <col><b>To run off at the mouth</b></col>, <cd>to
speak excessively.</cd> -- <col><b>To talk out of both sides of one's
mouth</b></col>, <cd>to say things which are
contradictory.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>The mouth</qex> of them that speak lies shall be
<qex>stopped</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lxiii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose <qex>mouths</qex> must be <qex>stopped</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Titus i. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 950 --></p>

<p><ent>Mouth</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mouth
<hw>Mouth</hw> <pr>(mou⟦th⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mouthed</conjf> <pr>(mou⟦th⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Mouthing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take
into the mouth; to seize or grind with the mouth or teeth; to chew; to
devour.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter with a voice affectedly big or swelling; to
speak in a strained or unnaturally sonorous manner; <as>as,
<ex>mouthing</ex> platitudes</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Mouthing</xex> big
phrases.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hare.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mouthing</qex> out his hollow oes and aes.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form or cleanse with the mouth; to lick, as a
bear her cub.</def> <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make mouths at.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>R. Blair.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouth</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mouth
<hw>Mouth</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To speak with a full,
round, or loud, affected voice; to vociferate; to rant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll bellow out for Rome, and for my country,⟦br⟧
And <qex>mouth</qex> at Caesar, till I shake the senate.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put mouth to mouth; to kiss.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make grimaces, esp. in ridicule or
contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Well I know, when I am gone,⟦br⟧
How she <qex>mouths</qex> behind my back.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mouthed</ent>⟦br⟧
